// exp_1.1   217. CONTAINS DUPLICATE I
AIM: Given an integer array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice in the array, and return false if every element is distinct.

Algorithm: Contains Duplicate (Using Hash Set)
Steps

Step 1: Create an empty hash set seen to store the elements that have already been visited.
Step 2: Traverse the array nums from the first element to the last.
Step 3: For each element num:
      Check whether num is already present in the hash set seen.
      If it is present, it means the element has appeared before, so return true because a duplicate exists.
      Otherwise, insert num into the hash set and continue to the next element.
Step 4: If all elements are processed and no duplicate is found, return false since every element is distinct.

class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
        for(int i =1;i<nums.size();i++){
            if(nums[i]== nums[i-1])
            return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
};

// exp_1.2   219. CONTAINS DUPLICATE II

AIM: Given an integer array nums and an integer k, return true if there are two distinct indices i and j in the array such that nums[i] == nums[j] and abs(i - j) <= k.

Algorithm: ContainsDuplicate(nums)

Step 1: Create an empty hash set 'seen'.
Step 2: Traverse each element 'num' in nums.
Step 3: If num exists in seen, return True.
Step 4: Otherwise, insert num into seen.
Step 5: Repeat until all elements are checked.
Step 6: Return False if no duplicate is found.
Step 7: Stop.

class Solution {
public:
    bool containsNearbyDuplicate(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        unordered_map<int, int> mp;

        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            if (mp.count(nums[i]) && i - mp[nums[i]] <= k)
                return true;

            mp[nums[i]] = i;
        }

        return false;
    }
};
